    "content": "## Theorem: aime_1987_p8\n\nTheorem: aime_1987_p8\nVariables: n (integer)\nGiven: h₀ : 0 < n\nGiven: h₁ : ∃! k, (8 : ℝ) / 15 < n / (n + k) ∧ (n : ℝ) / (n + k) < 7 / 13\nProve: n ≤ 112\n\nGoal: n ≤ 112\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"The two strict inequalities force k to lie in a very narrow interval determined by n; uniqueness of such an integer k means that interval contains exactly one integer, which can only happen when n is at most 112.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Rewrite both inequalities as bounds on k.\",\n    \"Use the uniqueness hypothesis to show the interval contains exactly one integer.\",\n    \"Convert the interval length condition into an inequality involving n.\",\n    \"Solve the resulting inequality to obtain the bound n ≤ 112.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"For any integer k satisfying (8 : ℝ) / 15 < n / (n + k) and (n : ℝ) / (n + k) < 7 / 13, we have 13n/7 < n + k < 15n/8.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since n > 0 and n + k must be positive for the displayed fractions to be positive, we may cross-multiply without changing the direction of the inequalities. The first inequality gives 8(n+k) < 15n, hence n+k < 15n/8. The second gives 13n < 7(n+k), hence 13n/7 < n+k.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₀\",\n        \"basic algebraic manipulation of inequalities\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Equivalently, any such k must satisfy 6n/7 < k < 7n/8.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Subtract n from each part of the inequalities in step 1: 13n/7 - n < k and k < 15n/8 - n. Simplifying gives 6n/7 < k < 7n/8.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"simplification of fractions\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The interval (6n/7, 7n/8) contains exactly one integer k.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is exactly the content of the uniqueness hypothesis h₁: there exists a unique integer k satisfying the two inequalities. By step 2, those inequalities are equivalent to k lying in the open interval (6n/7, 7n/8).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₁\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The length of the interval (6n/7, 7n/8) is n/56.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Its length is 7n/8 - 6n/7 = (49n - 48n)/56 = n/56.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"arithmetic with fractions\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If an open interval contains exactly one integer, then its length is less than 2, and in this specific situation this forces n/56 < 2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"An open interval of length at least 2 must contain at least two integers, because any interval of length 2 contains two consecutive integers or more. Since step 3 says there is exactly one integer in the interval, its length must be less than 2. Therefore n/56 < 2.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"pigeonhole principle for integers in intervals\",\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 4\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"n < 112.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From n/56 < 2, multiply both sides by 56 > 0 to get n < 112.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"positivity of 56\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Therefore n ≤ 112.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since n is an integer and n < 112, it follows that n ≤ 111, hence certainly n ≤ 112.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"integrality of n\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"n ≤ 112\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
