    "content": "## Theorem: aime_1994_p4\n\nTheorem: aime_1994_p4\nVariables: n (integer)\nGiven: h₀ : 0 < n\nGiven: h₀ : ∑ k in finset.Icc 1 n, int.floor (real.logb 2 k) = 1994\nProve: n = 312\n\nGoal: n = 312\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"For each integer k, floor(log_2 k) is constant on intervals [2^m, 2^{m+1}-1], so the sum becomes a weighted count of powers of 2 and can be evaluated by grouping terms into dyadic blocks.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Rewrite the sum by grouping integers k according to the value of floor(log_2 k).\",\n    \"Compute the contribution of each dyadic block [2^m, 2^{m+1}-1].\",\n    \"Express the total sum in terms of the largest power of 2 below n.\",\n    \"Use the equation 1994 to determine that largest power and hence determine n.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"For every integer m ≥ 0 and every integer k with 2^m ≤ k ≤ 2^{m+1}-1, we have floor(log_2 k) = m.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By definition of logarithm base 2, 2^m ≤ k < 2^{m+1} is equivalent to m ≤ log_2 k < m+1. Taking the floor gives floor(log_2 k)=m.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of real logarithm base 2\",\n        \"definition of floor\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If 2^r ≤ n < 2^{r+1}, then ∑_{k=1}^n floor(log_2 k) = ∑_{m=0}^{r-1} m·2^m + r·(n-2^r+1).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By the previous step, the terms with k in [2^m,2^{m+1}-1] all contribute m. For m<r, the full block [2^m,2^{m+1}-1] lies inside [1,n] and has 2^m terms; the last partial block [2^r,n] contributes r for each of its n-2^r+1 terms.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"counting integers in an interval\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"For every integer r ≥ 1, ∑_{m=0}^{r-1} m·2^m = (r-2)2^r + 2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a standard finite geometric-sum identity, obtainable for example by differentiating the geometric series or by induction.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"finite geometric series identity\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If 2^r ≤ n < 2^{r+1}, then ∑_{k=1}^n floor(log_2 k) = (r-2)2^r + 2 + r(n-2^r+1) = rn - 2^{r+1} + r + 2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Substitute the closed form from the previous step into the block decomposition and simplify algebraically.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The value r = 8 is the unique integer such that 1994 lies between the sums for n = 2^r-1 and n = 2^{r+1}-1, and in fact 1994 = 8·n - 2^9 + 10 forces n = 312.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"We test the dyadic block containing n. Since the sum at n=2^r-1 equals (r-2)2^r+2 and at n=2^{r+1}-1 equals (r-1)2^{r+1}+2, the target 1994 falls in the block r=8 because 1794 ≤ 1994 < 3842. Then the formula from the previous step gives 1994 = 8n - 512 + 10, so 8n = 2496 and n = 312.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"comparison of integers\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"n = 312.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The previous step determines n uniquely.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"312\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
