    "content": "## Theorem: amc12a_2003_p24\n\nTheorem: amc12a_2003_p24\nVariables: a, b (real)\nProve: is_greatest {y : ℝ | ∃ (a b : ℝ), 1 < b ∧ b ≤ a ∧ y = real.logb a (a/b) + real.logb b (b/a)} 0\n\nGoal: is_greatest {y : ℝ | ∃ (a b : ℝ), 1 < b ∧ b ≤ a ∧ y = real.logb a (a/b) + real.logb b (b/a)} 0\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"Rewrite the logarithms using change-of-base so the expression becomes a simple function of x = log_a b, which reduces the problem to showing x + 1/x ≥ 2 for x > 0.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Convert the given logarithmic expression into a form involving only one variable.\",\n    \"Use the condition 1 < b ≤ a to determine the sign and range of that variable.\",\n    \"Apply AM-GM (or an equivalent inequality) to bound the expression from below by 0.\",\n    \"Exhibit equality at a=b to show the bound is sharp and hence the greatest value is 0.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"For any real numbers a,b with 1 < b ≤ a, the expression y = log_a(a/b) + log_b(b/a) is well-defined and can be rewritten as y = 1/log_b(a) - log_b(a).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since 1 < b ≤ a, both a and b are positive and not equal to 1, so the logarithms are defined. Using the change-of-base identity, log_a(a/b) = 1 - log_a(b) and log_b(b/a) = -log_b(a); also log_a(b) = 1/log_b(a). Combining these gives the stated form.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"change-of-base formula for logarithms\",\n        \"properties of logarithms\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If x = log_b(a), then x ≥ 1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because 1 < b ≤ a and b > 1, the logarithm base b is increasing on positive reals. Since a ≥ b, we get log_b(a) ≥ log_b(b) = 1.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"monotonicity of logarithm for base greater than 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"For x ≥ 1, the quantity 1/x - x is at most 0.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since x ≥ 1, we have 1/x ≤ 1 ≤ x, hence 1/x - x ≤ 0. Equivalently, x - 1/x ≥ 0.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"order properties of real numbers\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Therefore every admissible value y satisfies y ≤ 0.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By step 1, y = 1/x - x with x = log_b(a). By step 2, x ≥ 1, and step 3 then gives y ≤ 0.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The value y = 0 is attainable.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Take a = b > 1. Then log_a(a/b) = log_a(1) = 0 and log_b(b/a) = log_a(1) = 0, so y = 0.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"properties of logarithms\",\n        \"existence of admissible example\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The greatest possible value of y is 0.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Step 4 shows no admissible pair can produce y > 0, and step 5 shows y = 0 is achieved. Hence 0 is the greatest value in the set.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"step 5\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"0\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
