ion becomes a comparison between a strictly increasing exponential term and a logarithmic term; standard monotonicity/convexity arguments show the two graphs intersect exactly twice, and one intersection is already known to be x = √2.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"monotonicity of exp\",\n        \"monotonicity of ln\",\n        \"strict convexity of exponential functions\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"S has exactly two elements, one of which is √2, and the other is a positive real number less than 4.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By h₀, membership in S is exactly the set of positive solutions to the defining equation. Since there are exactly two positive solutions and one is √2, S consists of those two numbers. The second solution lies below 4 by the shape of the two curves in step 3.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₀\",\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The sum of the elements of S is at least 2 and less than 6.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since √2 ∈ S and all elements of S are positive, the sum is at least √2 > 1, and because there are exactly two positive elements with the second one less than 4, the total sum is less than √2 + 4 < 6. Therefore 2 ≤ ∑ k in S, k and ∑ k in S, k < 6.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"basic inequalities\",\n        \"positivity of elements of S\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"2 ≤ ∑ k in S, k ∧ ∑ k in S, k < 6\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
