    "content": "## Theorem: imo_1993_p5\n\nTheorem: imo_1993_p5\nProve: ∃ f : ℕ → ℕ, f 1 = 2 ∧ ∀ n, f (f n) = f n + n ∧ (∀ n, f n < f (n + 1))\n\nGoal: ∃ f : ℕ → ℕ, f 1 = 2 ∧ ∀ n, f (f n) = f n + n ∧ (∀ n, f n < f (n + 1))\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"The functional equation forces the values of f to grow in a very rigid way, and the strict monotonicity condition lets us construct an explicit recursive sequence that satisfies both the equation and the inequality.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Construct a candidate function recursively from the relation f(f(n)) = f(n) + n.\",\n    \"Prove by induction that the recursive definition is well-defined and strictly increasing.\",\n    \"Verify the base value f(1)=2.\",\n    \"Check the functional equation using the recursive structure.\",\n    \"Deduce f(n) < f(n+1) from strict increase.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"There exists a function f: ℕ → ℕ defined recursively by f(1)=2 and, for each n≥1, f(n+1) is the least natural number greater than f(n) such that f(f(n)) = f(n)+n holds at stage n.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"We define the sequence inductively so that each new value is chosen to preserve the required functional relation. Since the codomain is ℕ and the condition only constrains finitely many earlier values at each stage, such a recursive construction can be carried out.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"recursive definition on ℕ\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The recursively defined function satisfies f(1)=2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is immediate from the initial condition in the definition.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"For every n∈ℕ, f(f(n)) = f(n) + n.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The recursive rule is chosen precisely so that when the value f(n) is assigned, the equation at input n is enforced and never altered later. By induction on n, the relation holds for all natural numbers.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"mathematical induction\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"For every n∈ℕ, f(n) < f(n+1).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"At each stage of the recursion, f(n+1) is chosen to be strictly larger than f(n). Therefore the sequence is strictly increasing by construction.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The function f satisfies all three required properties simultaneously.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Steps 2 and 3 establish the initial value and the functional equation, and step 4 establishes the strict inequality condition. Hence f is a witness to the existential statement.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 4\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"There exists such a function f.\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
