    "content": "## Theorem: mathd_numbertheory_126\n\nTheorem: mathd_numbertheory_126\nVariables: x, a (integer)\nGiven: h₀ : 0 < x ∧ 0 < a\nGiven: h₁ : nat.gcd a 40 = x + 3\nGiven: h₂ : nat.lcm a 40 = x * (x + 3)\nGiven: h₃ : ∀ b : ℕ, 0 < b → nat.gcd b 40 = x + 3 ∧ nat.lcm b 40 = x * (x + 3) → a ≤ b\nProve: a = 8\n\nGoal: a = 8\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"For any positive integer a, gcd(a,40) and lcm(a,40) satisfy gcd(a,40)·lcm(a,40)=40a; combining this with the given formulas forces x+3 to be a divisor of 40 and determines x uniquely.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Use the standard gcd-lcm product identity to relate x and a.\",\n    \"Substitute the given expressions for gcd and lcm and solve for x.\",\n    \"Use the fact that gcd(a,40) divides 40 to narrow down x.\",\n    \"Check the resulting value satisfies the equations and conclude a=8.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"nat.gcd a 40 * nat.lcm a 40 = 40 * a.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the standard identity for positive integers: gcd(m,n)·lcm(m,n)=m·n. Since h₀ gives 0<a and 40 is positive, the identity applies to a and 40.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"gcd_lcm_mul\",\n        \"step 0\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"(x + 3) * (x * (x + 3)) = 40 * a.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By h₁, nat.gcd a 40 = x + 3, and by h₂, nat.lcm a 40 = x * (x + 3). Substituting these into the identity from the previous step gives the stated equation.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"h₁\",\n        \"h₂\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"x + 3 divides 40.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since nat.gcd a 40 = x + 3, the number x + 3 is a gcd with 40, so it must divide 40. Therefore x + 3 is a positive divisor of 40.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of gcd\",\n        \"h₁\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"x + 3 = 8.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The positive divisors of 40 are 1, 2, 4, 5, 8, 10, 20, and 40. Because x > 0 by h₀, we have x + 3 > 3, and from step 3 it must be one of these divisors. The only divisor compatible with the product relation in step 2 is x + 3 = 8, which gives x = 5.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"divisors of 40\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"a = 8.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From step 2 and x + 3 = 8, we get 8 * (x * 8) = 40a. Since x = 5 from step 4, this becomes 8 * 40 = 40a, hence a = 8.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"algebra\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"8\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization.\n\n## Previous attempt (failed)\nYour last formalization:\n{\n  \"status\": \"the_stated_theorem_is_false_with_the_given_h3\",\n  \"diagnostic\": \"The hypotheses as stated admit the counterexample x = 37, a = 1480: GCD(1480,40)=40=x+3 and LCM(1480,40)=1480=x*(x+3). The minimality condition h3 is also satisfied for this fixed x, since any positive b with GCD(b,40)=40 and LCM(b,40)=1480 must have b=1480 by the gcd-lcm product identity. Therefore no sound collection of universally true lemmas can make Z3 prove a == 8 from these hypotheses.\",\n  \"theorem\": {\n    \"variables\": [\n      {\n        \"name\": \"x\",\n        \"sort\": \"Int\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"a\",\n        \"sort\": \"Int\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"b\",\n        \"sort\": \"Int\"\n      }\n    ],\n    \"hypotheses\": [\n      \"And(0 < x, 0 < a)\",\n      \"GCD(a, 40) == x + 3\",\n      \"LCM(a, 40) == x * (x + 3)\",\n      \"ForAll([b], Implies(And(0 < b, GCD(b, 40) == x + 3, LCM(b, 40) == x * (x + 3)), a <= b))\"\n    ],\n    \"goal\": \"a == 8\"\n  },\n  \"lemmas\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"gcd_lcm_product_40\",\n      \"english\": \"For every positive integer m, gcd(m,40) times lcm(m,40) equals 40m.\",\n      \"vars\": [\n        {\n          \"name\": \"m\",\n          \"sort\": \"Int\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"body\": \"Implies(0 < m, GCD(m, 40) * LCM(m, 40) == 40 * m)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"name\": \"gcd_divides_40_and_argument\",\n      \"english\": \"If d is gcd(m,40) for positive m, then d is positive and divides both 40 and m.\",\n      \"vars\": [\n        {\n          \"name\": \"m\",\n          \"sort\": \"Int\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"name\": \"d\",\n          \"sort\": \"Int\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"body\": \"Implies(And(0 < m, GCD(m, 40) == d), And(0 < d, 40 % d == 0, m % d == 0))\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"name\": \"positive_divisors_of_40\",\n      \"english\": \"The positive integer divisors of 40 are exactly 1, 2, 4, 5, 8, 10, 20, and 40.\",\n      \"vars\": [\n        {\n          \"name\": \"d\",\n          \"sort\": \"Int\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"body\": \"Implies(And(0 < d, 40 % d == 0), Or(d == 1, d == 2, d == 4, d == 5, d == 8, d == 10, d == 20, d == 40))\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"instantiations\": [\n    {\n      \"lemma\": \"gcd_lcm_product_40\",\n      \"terms\": {\n        \"m\": \"a\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"lemma\": \"gcd_divides_40_and_argument\",\n      \"terms\": {\n        \"m\": \"a\",\n        \"d\": \"x + 3\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"lemma\": \"positive_divisors_of_40\",\n      \"terms\": {\n        \"d\": \"x + 3\"\n      }\n    }\n  ]\n}\n\nErrors:\n- Z3 returned unknown (timeout or incomplete reasoning). Simplify the formalization or add more targeted instantiations.\n\nFix these issues and return the corrected JSON object only."
